<p id="fs-id1165042931764">Step 3. Since <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>f</mi><mo>&#8242;</mo></msup></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><msup><mi>f</mi><mo>&#8242;</mo></msup></annotation-xml></semantics></math> switches sign from positive to negative as <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mi>x</mi></annotation-xml></semantics></math> increases through <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> has a local maximum at <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>&#8722;1</mn><mo>.</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>&#8722;1</mn><mo>.</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> Since <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>f</mi><mo>&#8242;</mo></msup></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><msup><mi>f</mi><mo>&#8242;</mo></msup></annotation-xml></semantics></math> switches sign from negative to positive as <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mi>x</mi></annotation-xml></semantics></math> increases through <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> has a local minimum at <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> These analytical results agree with the following graph.</p><figure id="CNX_Calc_Figure_04_05_003"><figcaption>The function <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mi>f</mi></annotation-xml></semantics></math> has a maximum at <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>&#8722;1</mn></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>&#8722;1</mn></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> and a minimum at <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math></figcaption>
<span data-type="media" id="fs-id1165042925692" data-alt="The function f(x) = x3 &#8211; 3x2 &#8211; 9x &#8211; 1 is graphed. It has a maximum at x = &#8722;1 and a minimum at x = 3. The function is increasing before x = &#8722;1, decreasing until x = 3, and then increasing after that.">
